10 (3) For operating under an expired shellfish lease agreement, if the violation
11 occurs within one month of the expiration of the agreement, the violation shall
12 be punishable only by issuance of a warning ticket pursuant to G.S. 113-140."
13 SECTION 15.(b) This section becomes effective December 1, 2025, and applies to
14 offenses committed on or after that date.
15
16 REQUIRE A STATEWIDE STUDY ON SHELLFISH AQUACULTURE LEASING AND
17 CURRENT MORATORIUMS ON SHELLFISH LEASING
18 SECTION 15.5.(a) Study. – The North Carolina Collaboratory (Collaboratory) shall
19 conduct a comprehensive study on shellfish aquaculture regulations to ensure a balanced
20 approach between economic development, environmental protection, and public access to coastal
21 waters. The study shall evaluate all of the following:
22 (1) The effectiveness of existing regulations and permitting governing shellfish
23 aquaculture leases.
24 (2) The history and policy bases for current permanent and temporary
25 moratoriums and whether to lift or modify existing moratoriums or enact
26 additional moratoriums on shellfish aquaculture leases.
27 (3) Best practices from other states for managing shellfish aquaculture.
28 (4) The economic impact of shellfish aquaculture expansion on coastal economies
29 and tourism.
30 (5) Potential and actual conflicts between shellfish aquaculture operations and
31 private property values, commercial or recreational fishing, boating, and other
32 coastal land and water uses.
33 (6) Environmental considerations, including water quality, seagrass protection,
34 and marine habitat impacts due to the presence or absence of shellfish
35 aquaculture in various coastal habitats.
36 (7) Regulatory, permitting, and environmental impact differences between
37 bottom and column leases.
38 (8) The role of local governments in shellfish aquaculture leases located in or
39 adjacent to their jurisdictions.
40 (9) Recommendations for a statewide framework on the regulation and permitting
41 of shellfish aquaculture that benefits the industry and the State while
42 mitigating conflicts with users of public trust waters.
43 SECTION 15.5.(b) Required Consultations. – In conducting its study, the
44 Collaboratory shall consult with the North Carolina Division of Marine Fisheries, the Marine
45 Fisheries Commission, and other stakeholders, including shellfish growers, commercial and
46 recreational fishermen, property owners, and coastal area local governments.
47 SECTION 15.5.(c) Report. – The Collaboratory shall submit an interim report with
48 preliminary findings to the Joint Legislative Oversight Committee on Agriculture and Natural
49 and Economic Resources no later than December 1, 2025, and a final report, including any
50 recommendations for legislative or regulatory changes, by May 1, 2026.
51
